## Phase 1 — Reconnaissance

**Attacker IP:** `254.198.150.19`  
**Date:** `26/Apr/2023`  
**Time Range:** `03:44:47` — `19:45:14`

### What Happened
The attacker began by browsing the web application normally, systematically testing different `postId` values to map out which pages existed and how the application responded to different inputs.

### Evidence from Log
```
254.198.150.19 - - [26/Apr/2023:19:44:47] "GET /post?postId=9"  200 ✅
254.198.150.19 - - [26/Apr/2023:19:44:47] "GET /post?postId=0"  404 ❌
254.198.150.19 - - [26/Apr/2023:19:44:47] "GET /post?postId="   400 ⚠️
254.198.150.19 - - [26/Apr/2023:19:44:47] "GET /post?postId=6"  200 ✅
254.198.150.19 - - [26/Apr/2023:19:45:12] "GET /post?postId=16" 404 ❌
254.198.150.19 - - [26/Apr/2023:19:45:12] "GET /post?postId=11" 404 ❌
254.198.150.19 - - [26/Apr/2023:19:45:12] "GET /post?postId=10" 200 ✅
```

### What the Responses Mean
| Response Code | Meaning | Attacker's Takeaway |
|---------------|---------|---------------------|
| `200` | Page exists | Valid post ID found |
| `404` | Page not found | Post ID doesn't exist |
| `400` | Bad request | Input rejected by server |

### Command Used
```bash
cat /root/Desktop/QuestionFiles/Open-Redirection/access.log
```

### Conclusion
The attacker was mapping the application — finding out which post IDs were valid (1–10) before moving to the next phase.

